{"award_age":74.0,"bio_image":"full\/83113f87ede78d7b130d13789167c771525ab619.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1929-05-06T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2007-03-27T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/a\/a6\/PaulLauterbur.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_Lauterbur","mini_bio":"<p><b>Paul Christian Lauterbur<\/b> (May 6, 1929 \u2013 March 27, 2007) was an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemist\" title=\"Chemist\">chemist<\/a> who shared the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 2003 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Peter_Mansfield\" title=\"Peter Mansfield\">Peter Mansfield<\/a> for his work which made the development of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Magnetic_resonance_imaging\" title=\"Magnetic resonance imaging\">magnetic resonance imaging<\/a> (MRI) possible.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Filler2009b_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_Lauterbur#cite_note-Filler2009b-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Lauterbur was a professor at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/State_University_of_New_York_at_Stony_Brook\" title=\"State University of New York at Stony Brook\" class=\"mw-redirect\">State University of New York at Stony Brook<\/a> from 1963 until 1985 where he conducted his research for the development of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/MRI\" title=\"MRI\" class=\"mw-redirect\">MRI<\/a>. In 1985 he became a professor along with his wife Joan at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana-Champaign\" title=\"University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign<\/a> for 22 years until his death in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Urbana,_Illinois\" title=\"Urbana, Illinois\">Urbana<\/a>. He never stopped working with undergraduates on research, and he served as a professor of chemistry, with appointments in bioengineering, biophysics, the College of Medicine at Urbana-Champaign and computational biology at the Center for Advanced Study.<sup id=\"cite_ref-pittsburghgazette_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Paul_Lauterbur#cite_note-pittsburghgazette-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Paul C. Lauterbur","place_of_birth":"Sidney, Ohio","place_of_death":"Urbana, Illinois","text":"Paul C. Lauterbur , Physiology or Medicine, 2003","year":2003.0}